statement.p:
Simplify the expression
\sqrt{147 y^{8}}
into the simplest radical form A \sqrt{C}, where A and C are either integers or monomials.  Assume y\geq 0.

Express the number
\left( \frac{2^{-4}}{3^{-2}} \right)^{-1}
as a reduced fraction.

Assume that a and b represent positive real numbers.  Simplify the expression
5 \sqrt{28 a^{5} b^{6}}
into the simplest radical form A \sqrt{C}, where A and C are either integers or monomials.

Change the radical
\sqrt{\frac{3}{8}\;}
into simplest radical form \frac{A}{B} \sqrt{C}, where A, B, and C are all integers.

static.solution:
  SOLUTION 



Using the log rules, we have
\begin{aligned}
e^{0.09 t} \amp = 26 \\
\ln{ \left( e^{0.09 t} \right)} \amp = \ln{(26)} \\
0.09 t \amp = \ln{(26)} \\
t \amp = \frac{\ln{(26)}}{0.09}
\end{aligned}

  SOLUTION 



(a) \ln{AB} = \ln{ A } + \ln{ B } = x + y



(b) \begin{aligned}
\ln{(A^{6} \cdot \sqrt{B})} \amp = \ln{( A^{6})} + \ln{( \sqrt{B}) } \\
 \amp = \ln{(A^{6})} + \ln{(B^{1/2})} \\
 \amp = 6 \ \ln{A} + \frac{1}{2} \ \ln{B} \\
 \amp = 6 x + \frac{y}{2}
\end{aligned}



(c) \frac{\ln{A}}{\ln{B}} = \frac{x}{y}



(d) \ln{ \left( \frac{A}{B} \right) } = \ln{A} - \ln{B} = x-y



Since x = \ln{A} and y = \ln{B}, we can rewrite these two logarithmic equations in terms of exponents A = e^x and B = e^x respectively.  Thus:



(e) AB = e^x \cdot e^y = e^{x+y}



(f) \ln(A-B)  = \ln(e^x - e^y)

